@page "/about/results"

<PageTitle>Understanding Your NBT Results</PageTitle>

<link rel="stylesheet" href="Pages/ContentPage.css" />

<div class="content-page">
    <FluentBreadcrumb>
        <FluentBreadcrumbItem Href="/">Home</FluentBreadcrumbItem>
        <FluentBreadcrumbItem Href="/about/results">Understanding Results</FluentBreadcrumbItem>
    </FluentBreadcrumb>

    <h1>Understanding Your NBT Results</h1>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>How NBT Results are Reported</h2>
        <p>
            NBT results are reported using performance levels that indicate your readiness for tertiary study. 
            Each test domain (Academic Literacy, Quantitative Literacy, and Mathematics) receives a separate performance level.
        </p>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>Performance Levels</h2>
        
        <div class="performance-level">
            <h3><FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.Trophy())" Color="@Color.Success" /> Proficient</h3>
            <p><strong>Proficient Upper / Proficient Lower</strong></p>
            <p>
                You are well prepared for the demands of tertiary study in this domain. You should be able to cope 
                with coursework requiring these skills without additional academic support.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="performance-level">
            <h3><FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.Target())" Color="@Color.Warning" /> Intermediate</h3>
            <p><strong>Intermediate Upper / Intermediate Lower</strong></p>
            <p>
                You are moderately prepared for tertiary study in this domain. You may need some educational support 
                or development to help you succeed in coursework requiring these skills.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="performance-level">
            <h3><FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.Flag())" Color="@Color.Error" /> Basic</h3>
            <p><strong>Basic Upper / Basic Lower</strong></p>
            <p>
                You will require substantial educational support or development to succeed in tertiary coursework 
                requiring these skills. Consider additional preparation or foundation programs.
            </p>
        </div>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>Test Domains Explained</h2>
        
        <h3><FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.BookOpen())" /> Academic Literacy (AL)</h3>
        <p>
            Measures your ability to read and understand academic texts, extract key information, and apply critical 
            reasoning skills. This is essential for all tertiary study areas.
        </p>

        <h3><FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.DataArea())" /> Quantitative Literacy (QL)</h3>
        <p>
            Assesses your ability to manage situations or solve problems using quantitative information in academic 
            and real-life contexts. Important for understanding data, statistics, and numerical arguments.
        </p>

        <h3><FluentIcon Value="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.Calculator())" /> Mathematics (MAT)</h3>
        <p>
            Evaluates your mathematical competency required for entry-level courses in mathematics-intensive programs 
            such as engineering, science, commerce, and technology.
        </p>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>Understanding Your Results Certificate</h2>
        <p>Your NBT results certificate includes:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Personal Details:</strong> Your name, NBT number, and ID number</li>
            <li><strong>Test Information:</strong> Test date, venue, and test type</li>
            <li><strong>Performance Levels:</strong> Separate levels for AL, QL, and MAT (if applicable)</li>
            <li><strong>Barcode:</strong> Unique identifier for verification purposes</li>
        </ul>
        <FluentMessageBar Intent="MessageIntent.Info" Style="margin-top: 1rem;">
            Each test you write will have a different barcode to distinguish between test attempts.
        </FluentMessageBar>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>Accessing Your Results</h2>
        <p>
            Results are typically released 2-3 weeks after the test date. You will receive an email notification 
            when your results are available.
        </p>
        <p><strong>To access your results:</strong></p>
        <ol>
            <li>Log in to your NBT account</li>
            <li>Navigate to "My Results"</li>
            <li>View or download your results certificate as a PDF</li>
        </ol>
        <FluentMessageBar Intent="MessageIntent.Warning" Style="margin-top: 1rem;">
            <strong>Important:</strong> You can only view and download results for fully paid tests. 
            Ensure all test fees are paid before the booking closing date.
        </FluentMessageBar>
    </FluentCard>

    <FluentCard class="info-card">
        <h2>How Universities Use NBT Results</h2>
        <p>
            Universities use NBT results in various ways alongside your school results:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Admissions Decisions:</strong> Some universities use NBT results as part of their admission criteria</li>
            <li><strong>Course Placement:</strong> Results may inform which courses or programs you're placed in</li>
            <li><strong>Support Services:</strong> Universities identify students who may benefit from additional academic support</li>
            <li><strong>Foundation Programs:</strong> Lower performance levels may indicate a need for foundation or extended programs</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Check with your chosen institution(s) to understand how they use NBT results in their admission and 
            placement processes.
        </p>
    </FluentCard>

    <div class="action-section">
        <FluentButton Appearance="Appearance.Accent" 
                    IconStart="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.SignIn())"
                    OnClick="@(() => Navigation.NavigateTo("/login"))">
            View My Results
        </FluentButton>
        <FluentButton Appearance="Appearance.Outline"
                    IconStart="@(new Icons.Regular.Size20.PersonAdd())"
                    OnClick="@(() => Navigation.NavigateTo("/register"))">
            Register for NBT
        </FluentButton>
    </div>
</div>

<style>
    .performance-level {
        margin: 1.5rem 0;
        padding: 1rem;
        border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-fill-rest);
    }

    .performance-level h3 {
        color: var(--accent-fill-rest);
        margin-top: 0;
    }
</style>

@code {
    [Inject] private NavigationManager Navigation { get; set; } = default!;
}
